tician Alhazen (roughly 1000 AD). Yet, Greek philosopher Aristophanes (c. 448 BC-380 BC) knew that glass could be used as a magnifying glass. Nevertheless it was not until roughly 150 AD that Ptolemy discovered the basic rules of light diffraction and wrote extensively on the subject. (The laws of diffraction was formulated much later by Snellius, between 1600 and 1620.)','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:03','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3704,'Venetian glass blowers, who had learned how to produce glass for reading stones, later constructed lenses that could be held in a frame in front of the eye instead of directly on the reading material. It was intended for use by one eye; the idea to frame two ground glasses using wood or horn, making them into a single unit was born in the 13th century.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:05','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3705,'In 1268 Roger Bacon made the first known scientific commentary on lenses for vision correction. Salvino D?Armate of Pisa and Alessandro Spina of Florence are often credited with the invention of spectacles around 1284 but there is no evidence to conclude this. The first mention of actual glasses is found in a 1289 manuscript when a member of the Popozo family wrote: ‚ÄúI am so debilitated by age that without the glasses known as spectacles, I would no longer be able to read or write.‚Äù In 1306, a monk of Pisa mentioned in a sermon: ‚ÄúIt is not yet 20 years since the art of making spectacles, one of the most useful arts on earth, was discovered.‚Äù But nobody mentioned the inventor.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:05','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3706,'In the Middle Ages wearing spectacles signified knowledge and learning. Painters of the time often included spectacles when portraying famous persons even when depicting people who lived before the known invention of spectacles. On numerous paintings the religious teacher Sofronius Eusebius Hieronymus (340 ‚Äì 420 AD) is portrayed with a lion, a skull and a pair of reading glasses. He is the patron saint of spectacle makers.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:05','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3707,'It actually is true that eating carrots can help you see better. Carrots contain Vitamin A, which feeds the chemicals that the eye shafts and cones are made of. The shafts capture black and white vision. The cones capture colour images.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:05','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3708,'The oldest known lens was found in the ruins of ancient Nineveh and was made of polished rock crystal.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:05','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3709,'In 1718, Edward Scarlett, a London optician, put arms on eyeglasses to hold them on the ears.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3710,'About one person in 30 is colour blind. More men than women are affected by colour blindness.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3711,'Healthy eyes are so sensitive to light that a candle burning in the dark can be detected 1,6km (1 mile) away. The human eye can distinguish about 10 million different colours. There currently is no machine that can achieve this remarkable feat.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3712,'In 1894, the president of the Royal Society, William Thomson, Lord Kelvin, predicted that radio had no future. The first radio factory was opened five years later. Today, there are more than one billion radio sets in the world, tuned to more than 33 000 radio stations around the world. He also predicted that heavier-than-air flying machines were impossible. The Wright Brother‚Äôs first flight covered a distance equal to only half the length of the wingspan of a Boeing 747. He also said, ‚ÄúX-rays will prove to be a hoax.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3713,'In the 6th century BC Greek mathematician Pythagoras said that earth is round ‚Äì but few agreed with him. Greek astronomer Aristarchos said in the 3rd century BC that earth revolves around the sun ‚Äì but the idea was not accepted. In the 2nd century BC Greek astronomer Erastosthenes accurately measured the distance around the earth at about 40,000 km (24,860 miles) ‚Äì but nobody believed him. In the 2nd century AD Greek astronomer Ptolemy stated that earth was the centre of the universe ‚Äì most people believed him for the next 1,400 years.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3714,'In the early 20th century a world market for only 4 million automobiles was made because ‚Äúthe world would run out of chauffeurs.‚Äù Shortly after the end of World War II (1945), the whole of Volkswagen, factory and patents, was offered free to Henry Ford II. He dismissed the Volkswagen Beetle as a bad design. Today, more than 70 million motorcars are produced every year. The Beetle became one of the best-selling vehicles of all time.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3715,'The telephone was not widely appreciated for the first 15 years because people did not see a use for it. In fact, in the British parliament it was mentioned there was no need for telephones because ‚Äúwe have enough messengers here.‚Äù Western Union believed that it could never replace the telegraph. In 1876, an internal memo read: ‚ÄúThis telephone has too many shortcomings to be seriously considered as a means of communication.‚Äù Even Mark Twain, upon being invited by Alexander Graham Bell to invest $5 000 in the new invention, could not see a future in the telephone.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3716,'Irish scientist, Dr. Dionysius Lardner (1793 ‚Äì 1859) didn‚Äôt believe that trains could contribute much in speedy transport. He wrote: ‚ÄúRail travel at high speed is not possible, because passengers ‚Äò would die of asphyxia‚Äô [suffocation].‚Äù Today, trains reach speeds of 500 km/h.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3717,'In 1927, H.M. Warner, Warner Brothers, asked, ‚ÄúWho the hell wants to hear actors talk?‚Äù In 1936, Radio Times editor Rex Lambert thought ‚ÄúTelevision won‚Äôt matter in your lifetime or mine.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:06','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3718,'In 1943, Thomas Watson, the chairman of IBM forecast a world market for ‚Äúmaybe only five computers.‚Äù Years before IBM launched the personal computer in 1981, Xerox had already successfully designed and used PCs internally‚Ä¶ but decided to concentrate on the production of photocopiers. Even Ken Olson, founder of Digital Equipment Corporation, said in 1977, ‚ÄúThere is no reason anyone would want a computer in their home.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3719,'After the invention of the transistor in 1947, several US electronics companies rejected the idea of a portable radio. Apparently it was thought nobody would want to carry a radio around. When Bell put the transistor on the market in 1952 they had few takers apart from a small japanese start-up called Sony. They introduced the transistor radio in 1954.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3720,'In 1894, A.A. Michelson, who with E.W. Morley seven years earlier experimentally demonstrated the constancy of the speed of light, said that the future of science would consist of ‚Äúadding a few decimal places to the results already obtained.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3721,'In 1954, a concert manager fired Elvis Presley, saying, ‚ÄúYou ought to go back to driving a truck.‚Äù In 1962, Decca Records rejected the Beatles, ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt like their sound, and guitar music is on the way out.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3722,'In 1966, Time Magazine predicted, ‚ÄúBy 2000, the machines will be producing so much that everyone in the U.S. will, in effect, be independently wealthy.‚Äù In that year too CoCo Chanel said about miniskirts: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a bad joke that won‚Äôt last. Not with winter coming.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3723,'Sometimes a few decimal places make a massive difference. Library House explains that investment banks rely on computer models to direct trading activity; in August 2007, Goldman Sachs? hedge funds and other quant funds were left exposed by a series of market swings, each of which their software predicted would occur only once every 100,000 years. Goldman Sachs required a $3 billion (‚Ç¨1.9 billion) bailout, with other banks joining the hand-out queue.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3724,'Perhaps the guy who got it wrong most was the commissioner of the US Office of Patents: in 1899, Charles H. Duell, Commissioner, assured President McKinley that ‚Äúeverything that can be invented has been invented.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3725,'To prophesy is extremely difficult ‚Äì especially with regard to the future. - Chinese proverb','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3726,'The tall chef‚Äôs hat is called a ‚Äútoque.‚Äù During the 16th and 17th centuries, toques came in all shapes: berets, stocking caps, and even pointed hats with tassels. During the 18th century the tall hat came into use to show order of importance among the kitchen staff.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3727,'One of the greatest chefs is Auguste Escoffier (1846-1935). He started working in his uncle‚Äôs restaurant at age 14 and went on to work in the world most famous hotels. Recognised as the ‚Äúking of chefs and the chef of kings.‚Äù During a visit to Paris, William II of Germany is said to have remarked to him: ‚ÄúI am the emperor of Germany, but you are the emperor of chefs.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3728,'Escoffier‚Äôs most famous recipe was Peach Melba, created for Australian opera star Nellie Melba (1861-1931) when she was staying at the Savoy in 1893. Dame Melba also liked her toast made in the way that today bears her name: Melba toast.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:07','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3729,'Worldwide, 20,000 brands of beer are brewed in 180 styles, from ales, lagers, pilsner and stouts to bitters, cream ales and iced beers.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3730,'Beer has been a popular beverage for a long time. Babylonian clay tablets show detailed recipes of beer making in 4300 BC. Beer was also brewed by the ancient Chinese, Assyrians and Incas.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3731,'An Egyptian text of 1600 BC gives 100 medical prescriptions using beer. A few years ago, the New Castle Brewery in England brewed 1,000 bottles Tutankhamun Ale from a 3,200-year old recipe found in the sun temple of Queen Nefertiti.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3732,'Commercial beer making was established in 1200 AD in present-day Germany. In 1506, the German Purity Law is issued, specifying that beer ingredients must only be water, barley, wheat and hops. Bottling of beer started in 1605.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3733,'Making beer\r\nBrewing is the process of changing water and grain into beer through a yeast catalyst. The quality of the water is extremely important. Hard water produce a bitter ale, soft water produce bitter lager. Barley or hops, or a combination of them, is used for the grain.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3734,'Getting dry grain ready for fermentation is called malting. The grain is steeped in water until it sprouts. The sprouting or germination is not allowed to end naturally but is interrupted either by drying or roasting in kilns.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3735,'Barley\r\nBarley has been a grain of choice for thousands of years. The longer the roasting of the malted barley, the darker the beer. Barley, or wheat beers have a sweet taste.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3736,'Hops\r\nHops are herbaceous climbing vines and look like a cross between pine cores and artichokes. The bitter, dry flavour of hops counterbalance the sweetness of malt.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3737,'Yeast\r\nSugars in the malted grains are converted into alcohol by yeast. Different yeast ferment sugars into different flavours. For ales, top fermentation yeast is used, while bottom fermentation yeast is used for lagers.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3738,'The beer making process starts by germinating the grain, then steeping the resulting malt in hot water to get the wort. Base wort contents means the percentage of wort in the beer before fermentation. The alcohol contents is roughly one third of the base wort contents.The wort is boiled (brewed) and hops are added. After brewing, fermentation starts by adding yeast. After fermentation, the wort is drown into tanks where it is allowed to condition or age. Yeast and hops are sometimes added in a secondary fermentation process.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3739,'Ales and Lagers\r\nAles, stouts and several other types of brews, like porter, are top-fermented. The top-fermentation yeast, Saccharomyces cerevisiae, usually produces stronger alcohol contents than the bottom-fermentation yeast, Saccharomyces carlsbergi, but the latter produces more quality-consistent brew. Lagers are bottom-fermented.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3740,'Ales usually are heavily hopped, and include bitters, brown ales, cream ales, mild ale, pale ale, India pale ale, barley wine and several other types. There are two types of the aboriginal ale still brewed in Europe. They are Belgian ‚Äúlambic‚Äù and Finnish ‚Äúsahti‚Äù, which is brewed from rye malt. They are brewed on wild yeast and spontaneous fermentation. Both have very distinct tastes.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3741,'The word ‚Äúlager‚Äù is German and means ‚Äústorage‚Äù, which refers to the lager (storage) fermentation. The main fermentation of both ales and lager are done on the similar temperature for 7-14 days. After that time the ale, depending on the type, may be ready for bottling. With lagers, this is only the start. After the main fermentation the beer is pumped into lager (storage) tanks with temperature some 10 deg C lower than room temperature. It is then let to mature and ferment for several weeks, usually 6-10 weeks. At 270 days, the longest lager fermentation is for that of Budejovicky Budvar brewery‚Äôs Bud Strong.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3742,'Best taste\r\nThe best taste usually is acquired at an alcohol contents of 4.7% ethanol per volume. Less than that results in a beer with a bland taste. More than that and the higher alcohols (butanol, pentanol etc) become overpowering and spoils the taste.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3743,'The strongest beer type by alcohol content is doppelbock, which is usually 8%-10% ethanol by its volume content. The strongest beer brand in production is German ‚ÄúEisbock‚Äù, with some 14% ethanol by volume.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3744,'Ice beer is produced by freezing the brew and filtering the ice crystals, increasing the alcohol content. This process was already known in the Middle Ages to ‚Äúcold-distil‚Äù brandy from wine, and the ancient Chinese produced rice hooch that way. The Canadians adopted the cold-distillation method for ice beer.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3745,'The oldest brewery in Munich, the Augustiner brewery, was founded in 1294, when, on the order of the bishop of Freising, an Augustinian monastery was established at the Haberfeld, just outside the gates of the city. Munich was famous for its breweries operated by monks.\r\nA true pilsner comes from the Pilsner, Czech Republic. The original pilsner was Pilsner Urquell (Plzensky Prazrod), meaning ‚ÄúThe Original Spring of Pilsen.‚Äù It still is one of the most popular pilsner in the world.\r\nThe first beer brewery in the US opened in Manhattan in 1623. But the oldest contiuing brewery, running since 1829 is Yuengling in Schuylkill County in Pennsylvania.\r\nThe first Octoberfest was held in 1810 in Munich, Germany. It started as a wedding celebration.\r\nL√∂wenbrau of Munich was founded 1373.\r\nThe Czech Republic has the highest per capita beer consumption in the world, at 155 litres (40 gal).\r\nSake, the Japanese rice brew, is closer to beer than wine by its production method.\r\nThe English word ‚Äúbrewer‚Äù refers to a male beer-maker; ‚Äúbrewster‚Äù to a female.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:08','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3746,'| Animals | Arts & literature | Body | Earth & universe | Factoids | Food | History | Inventions | Money | Movies & TV | Music | People | Politics | Religion | Science | Sports | Statistics | Vehicles | War |','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3747,'Is a world population of 6 billion too many? Compare that with animals. There are more than a million animal species. There are 6,000 species of reptiles, 73,000 kinds of spiders, and 3,000 types of lice. For each person there is about 200 million insects. The 4,600 kinds of mammals represent a mere 0,3% of animals and the 9000 kinds of birds only 0,7%. The most numerous bird specie is the red-billed quelea of southern Africa. There are an estimated 100 trillion of them.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3748,'Mammals are the only animals with flaps around the ears.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3749,'African elephants only have four teeth to chew their food with.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3750,'There are about one billion cattle in the world of which 200 million are in India.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3751,'A house fly lives only 14 days.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3752,'A dog was the first in space and a sheep, a duck and a rooster the first to fly in a hot air balloon.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3753,'The Big Five is a group of animals of Africa: cape buffalo, elephant, leopard, lion and rhino. The term ‚ÄúBig Five‚Äù was coined by hunters who referred to the difficulty in hunting these wild animals because of their ferocity when cornered.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3754,'The oldest breed of dog is the Saluki.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3755,'The bee hummingbird of Cuba is the smallest bird in the world.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3756,'An ostrich can run up to 70 km/h (43mph).','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3757,'An annoyed camel will spit at a person.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3758,'The world‚Äôs smallest dog is the Chihuahua, which means ‚Äútiny dog in the sky.‚Äù','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3759,'Pea crabs (the size of a pea) are the smallest crabs in the world.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3760,'75% of wild birds die before they are 6 months old.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:09','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3761,'The pig is rated the fourth most intelligent animal but are mentioned only twice in the Bible','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3762,'Sheep are mentioned 45 times and goats 88 times in the Bible. Dogs are mentioned 14 times and lions 89 times, but domestic cats are not mentioned.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3763,'Pork is the world‚Äôs most widely-eaten meat.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3764,'In Denmark there are twice as many pigs as people.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3765,'Dinosaurs did not eat grass: there weren‚Äôt any at that time.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3766,'The coyote is a member of the dog family and its scientific name, ‚Äúcanis latrans‚Äù means barking dog.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3767,'A giraffe can clean its ears with its 50cm (20 in) tongue.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3768,'A group of geese on the ground is a gaggle ‚Äì a group of geese in the air is a skein.\r\nMore animal collective nouns','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3769,'The South American giant anteater eats more than 30,000 ants a day.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3770,'It is impossible to out-swim a shark ‚Äì sharks reach speeds of 70 km/h (44 mph). Humans can run about 35 km/h (21 mph).','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3771,'The sailfish is the fastest swimmer, reaching 109 km/h (68 mph).','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3772,'The slowest fish is the Sea Horse, which moves along at about 0.016 km/h (0.01 mph).','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3773,'Dolphins can reach 60 km/h (37 mph).','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3774,'Of the 650 types of leeches, only the Hirudo medicinalis is used for medical treatments.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3775,'The heart of a blue whale is the size of a small car.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3776,'The tongue of a blue whale is as long as an elephant.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3777,'The scales of a crocodile are made of ceratin, the same substance that hooves and fingernails are made of.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3778,'A crocodile‚Äôs tongue is attached to the roof of its mouth and cannot move it.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3779,'A snail has two pairs of tentacles on its head. One pair is longer than the other and houses the eyes. The shorter pair is used for smelling and feeling its way around.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:10','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3780,'The heaviest crustacean ever found was a lobster weighing 19 kg (42 lb), caught in 1934.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','2015-04-15 23:19:11','0001-01-01 00:00:00',6),(3781,'The largest jellyfish ever caught measured 2,3 m (7‚Äô6?) across the bell with a tentacle of 36 m (120 ft) long.','http://www.didyouknow.cd/','201